# Chapter 9 — Async + streams

`await` lets you yield to a scheduled task. `delay` + `force` build lazy streams — infinite sequences you consume on demand.

## Delay and force

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define lazy-42 (delay (begin (display \"computing…\") (newline) 42)))
(force lazy-42)
</pre>

## A tiny stream

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define (ints-from n)
  (cons n (delay (ints-from (+ n 1)))))

(define (stream-take s n)
  (if (= n 0)
      '()
      (cons (car s) (stream-take (force (cdr s)) (- n 1)))))

(stream-take (ints-from 1) 5)
</pre>

## Await

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(await (list 1 2 3))
</pre>

> **Sakura says**
>
> Streams are the Lisp answer to iterators. You get the same \"one at a time, infinite in principle\" feel — without a generator syntax.

> **Warning**
>
> If your `await` never resolves, the fuel budget catches it. The error you'll see is `fuel exhausted`. Increase the fuel or fix the promise — usually the latter.

---
